buttons.subtitle: How Do You Eat Lobster
buttons.title: How To Eat A Lobster Guide
buttons.snippet: Use your cracker on the widest sides of the lobster claw, crunch down and then, using a fork or picker, remove the large chunk of lobster meat in one swift movement. Be sure to wiggle the smaller part of each claw too and gently pull out any smaller bits of lobster meat.

buttons.subtitle: What Is Lobster Made Of?
buttons.title: Lobster - Wikipedia
buttons.snippet: The lobster's thorax is composed of maxillipeds, appendages that function primarily as mouthparts, and pereiopods, appendages that serve for walking and for gathering food. The abdomen includes pleopods (also known as swimmerets), used for swimming, as well as the tail fan, composed of uropods and the telson.

buttons.subtitle: Lobster Taste
buttons.title: What Does Lobster Taste Like? Why People Love It | Fishermen's Net
buttons.snippet: Lobster has a fishy taste but not as strong as other seafood. You can use spices to add flavor to the lobster, but you should not use too much. Using too much seasoning will overwhelm your lobster flavor. You won't be able to tell if you're eating lobster or lobster spices.

buttons.subtitle: What Do Lobsters Eat
buttons.title: Diet & Digestion - Lobster Institute - University of Maine
buttons.snippet: It was once thought that lobsters were scavengers, and ate primarily dead things. However, lobsters are really more opportunists, catching mainly fresh food which includes fish, crabs, clams, mussels, sea urchins. Lobsters are also cannibalistic and sometimes will eat other lobsters.

buttons.subtitle: Lobster Eggs
buttons.title: Fun Facts About Luscious Lobsters | NOAA Fisheries
buttons.snippet: Yes, lobsters lay eggs. A freshly-laid lobster egg is the size of the head of a pin (1/16"). A 1-pound female lobster usually carries approximately 8000 eggs. A 9-pound female may carry more than 100,000 eggs.

buttons.subtitle: Lobsters Habitat
buttons.title: Habitat - Lobster Institute - The University of Maine
buttons.snippet: Where do Lobsters Live? Lobsters are benthic, living on the bottom of the ocean. They prefer temperatures from 15-18°C (59-64°F) and salinities of 20-25 ppt. The American lobster can be found on the east coast of North America, from Newfoundland to North Carolina.
